sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322150
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Bacterial luciferase (luxAB) blue shifted by lumazine protein, with promoter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Bacterial luciferase from X. luminescens (luxAB) with Lumazine protein which shifts its spectrum towards blue. Note that LuxAB uses decanal as a substrate, this needs to be added or synthesised by the bacteria (Decanal production is coded for by BBa_K322312).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Richard Partridge Hicks
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Decanal must be added or synthesised by LuxCDE (see Ba_K322312). Note that this part also contains a LacZ fragment between the promoter and luxAB.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322149
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Bacterial luciferase (luxAB) blue shifted by lumazine protein
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The spectral output of the bacterial luciferase from X. luminescens is known to shift towards blue wavelengths in presence of lumazine protein (lumP). This part is made of both these biobricks.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Richard Partridge Hicks
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LuxAB uses decanal as a substrate. This can either be added to the medium, or can be synthesised by providing lucCDE (BBa_K322312).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322139
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Richard Partridge-Hicks and Maria Kowal
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Source: genomic DNA of Xenorhabdus (Photorhabdus) luminescens Hb (actually, we used our BioBrick from last year, BBa_K216016 as template).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Notes: we prepared this for two reasons: firstly to resolve an issue with the SpeI site in our submitted version of K216008 (for some reason, every clone we sequenced seemed to have an error, not always the same error, in the suffix SpeI site), and to put it in pSB1C3, since this seems to be the new standard vector for the Registry.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J33207
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part (submitted in pSB1A2) consists of the lac promoter and lacZ' gene, encoding the N-terminal 76 amino acid residues of LacZ, sufficient to complement the lacZ-delta-M15 mutation for blue-white selection on Xgal plates. A SacI site has been introduced at the 3' end, overlapping the XbaI site of the Biobrick prefix. This is designed to be used as a cloning vector for making new biobricks. PCR primers can be designed with a SacI site in one primer and an SpeI site in the other. This removes the necessity for an excessively long non-complementary tail on one primer bearing either the full biobrick prefix or suffix. The PCR product can then be digested with SacI and SpeI for insertion into this plasmid, replacing the Plac-lacZ' cassette. Recombinant plasmids will then be white on IPTG/Xgal plates, whereas any that still contain the original insert will be blue. We have used this strategy to prepare several biobricks, including BBa_J33204, which contains the xylE gene encoding catechol-2,3-dioxygenase. (For making biobricks that contain lacZ', BBa_J33204 can be used in the same way; in this case, clones with plasmids that still contain xylE will turn yellow on addition of a drop of 10 mM catechol.)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was amplified from E. coli BL21 genomic DNA using primers based on published sequence (Genbank accession J01636, gi:146575). The annotation shown here is based on that associated with this Genbank entry. The sequence shown here is derived by sequencing the construct.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Note that the SacI site overlaps the SpeI site. The Biobrick prefix ends ...TCTAGAG. When this is added to the CTC at the start of the sequence shown here, the SacI site, GAGCTC, is generated.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K322007
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Lumazine protein (LumP). Causes blue shift of P. phosphoreum luciferase emmision spectrum.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the lumazine protein of Photobacterium phosphoreum. Lumazine protein (LumP) of Photobacterium phosphoreum is a small protein which binds a fluorescent pteridine, 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1'-D-ribityl)lumazine, as cofactor. In P. phosphoreum, it acts to shift the wavelength of light emitted by luciferase, LuxAB, from 495 nm to a shorter wavelength, around 475 nm (O'Kane et al, 1990 and references cited therein).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Chris French and Maria Kowal
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Source: genomic DNA of Photobacterium phosphoreum.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We submitted a version of lumP last year (BBa_K216007), but made a new one since we were having some issues working with our clone (lots of red colonies). So we made a new one in pSB1C3 starting from the original PCR product. On sequencing this (as well as looking at the sequence results from the original plasmids, M1117 and M1118) it was found that the sequence differed from the one we had submitted in a number of mutations, some silent, some not.
